Description: Terracotta mould-made protome of a woman in Late Archaic style. Back, headdress and right ear and blue left earring preserved. Made of micaeous East Greek clay. White-Coated and painted blue.
Curator's comments: Archaic East Greek protome of late Archaic date (550BC to 480 BC). The fabric is similar to that of figurines of an East Greek origin. Often identified as ‘Rhodian’ though numerous production places are likely across East Greece. Parallels from Lindos, Rhodes, of Type A1 dated ‘late Archaic’, after 525BC (Blinkenberg 1931, 591, pl.116, nos 2463 and 2465). A number of fragments from the same type of protome may come from the same piece (Cambridge Museum of Classical Archaeology NA452, NA761 and possibly NA831; Cambridge, Fitzwilliam Museum GR.8.1899; British Museum GR 2011,5009.275). Similar protomes were found in Samos is dated to the third quarter of the 6th century BC (Tsakos 2007, 194, pl.26.2) and from Olynthus dated 6th century BC (Robinson 1952, 73-4, pl.1-3, nos 1-2). Falls into Croissant's Aeolis and Clazomenae types dated between 540 and 510 BC (Croissant 1983,164 nos 82-3 and 95-107, Types F4 and G3). For context, function and details on protome parallels and fragments from Naukratis see protome records from Cambridge Museum of Classical Archaeology (NA350, NA355, NA354, NA353, NA390, NA850, NA426, NA803 and NA509).
